# 10 — API Response Shaping

> **Send only what the client needs. Nothing more. Nothing less.**

---

## What is API Response Shaping?

API Response Shaping is the practice of **transforming and filtering the data your API sends back** before it reaches the client.

Instead of dumping a raw database row (with internal IDs, sensitive fields, snake_case columns, and irrelevant metadata) directly into the HTTP response, you explicitly define the shape of what goes out.

This might sound obvious. It isn't. Most developers skip it when starting out — and they pay for it later.

---

## The Problem It Solves

Imagine a `users` table in PostgreSQL:

```
id | email | password_hash | role | created_at | updated_at | internal_notes | stripe_customer_id
```

Without response shaping, a naive API returns **all of it**.

Now your frontend has `password_hash` and `stripe_customer_id` floating around in state. Your client knows more about your DB schema than it should. You've accidentally over-exposed data. And when you rename a column in your DB, the API breaks the client silently.

Response shaping closes this gap.

---

## Core Techniques

### 1. Field Selection (Explicit Allow-lists)

Instead of returning everything, you define exactly which fields are included:

```js
// ❌ Bad — raw DB row goes out
return res.json(user);

// ✅ Good — shaped output
return res.json({
  id: user.id,
  name: user.name,
  email: user.email,
  avatarUrl: user.avatar_url,
});
```

### 2. Key Renaming (snake_case → camelCase)

Your database uses `snake_case`. Your frontend uses `camelCase`. Without shaping, your client sees `created_at`, `avatar_url`, `is_active`. With shaping, it gets clean JavaScript:

```js
function shapeUser(user) {
  return {
    id: user.id,
    fullName: user.full_name,
    avatarUrl: user.avatar_url,
    createdAt: user.created_at,
    isActive: user.is_active,
  };
}
```

### 3. Computed Fields

You can add derived values that don't exist as columns:

```js
function shapeUser(user) {
  return {
    id: user.id,
    name: user.name,
    // Computed — doesn't exist in DB
    initials: user.name.split(' ').map(n => n[0]).join('').toUpperCase(),
    memberSince: new Date(user.created_at).getFullYear(),
  };
}
```

### 4. Role-Based Shaping

Different clients (admin vs public user vs third-party) should get different shapes:

```js
function shapeUser(user, viewerRole) {
  const base = {
    id: user.id,
    name: user.name,
    avatarUrl: user.avatar_url,
  };

  if (viewerRole === 'admin') {
    return {
      ...base,
      email: user.email,
      role: user.role,
      lastLogin: user.last_login_at,
    };
  }

  return base;
}
```

### 5. Nested / Relational Shaping

When your query joins tables, shape each nested resource too:

```js
function shapePost(post) {
  return {
    id: post.id,
    title: post.title,
    body: post.body,
    author: {
      id: post.author_id,
      name: post.author_name,
      avatarUrl: post.author_avatar_url,
    },
    tags: post.tags.map(t => ({ id: t.id, label: t.name })),
    publishedAt: post.published_at,
  };
}
```

### 6. Envelope / Pagination Wrapper

A consistent response envelope makes it easy for clients to handle pagination, errors, and metadata:

```js
function paginated(data, total, page, pageSize) {
  return {
    data,
    meta: {
      total,
      page,
      pageSize,
      totalPages: Math.ceil(total / pageSize),
    },
  };
}
```

