## When to Use It

| Situation | Use Response Shaping? |
|---|---|
| Any public API | ✅ Always |
| Any API with auth | ✅ Always |
| Internal microservices (same team) | ✅ Recommended |
| Quick prototyping / dev-only endpoints | ⚠️ Maybe skip for speed |

---

## Where to Put Shapers

There are a few patterns for organising your shapers depending on your stack:

**Next.js API Routes / Route Handlers** → put shapers in `lib/shapers/` or `utils/shapers/`

**Laravel** → use API Resources (`php artisan make:resource UserResource`)

**Express/Node** → shapers in `src/mappers/` or `src/transformers/`

**GraphQL** → resolvers handle shaping by design

---

## Real-World Context

Every serious API you've used does this. Stripe never sends you their internal DB columns. GitHub's REST API shapes every response. Shopify's API has versioned resource shapes. This pattern is the difference between an API that exposes your data model and an API that exposes your product's contract.

---

## Key Takeaway

> **Your API is a contract. Your database is an implementation detail. Response shaping keeps them separate.**

When the DB changes, update the shaper. The contract stays stable. The client stays unbroken.

